An Act relative to education and prevention of sudden unexpected death in epilepsy and other
related epilepsy mortalities.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1. Section 4G of chapter 111 of the General Laws, as appearing in the 2022
2 Official Edition, is hereby amended by adding the following paragraph:-
3 The department shall develop informational resources on sudden unexpected death in
4 epilepsy or “SUDEP” and other epilepsy-related mortalities to provide to epilepsy patients, their
5 families and health care providers. The information shall include, but not be limited to: (i)
6 current and evidence-based information about SUDEP and other epilepsy-related mortality risk
7 factors; (ii) contact information for non-profit organizations that provide support services for
8 patients with epilepsy conditions; and (iii) information on mitigating the risks of SUDEP and
9 other epilepsy-related mortalities. The department shall make the informational resources
10 available on its website in a manner that is easily accessible to patients, families and health care
11 providers.
1 of 2

12 SECTION 2. Not later than 1 year following the passage of this act, the department of
13 public health shall submit to the clerks of the house of representatives and the senate and the
14 joint committee on public health a report including a summary of relevant metrics, which shall
15 include, but not be limited to: (i) the information gathered for the informational resources; (ii) its
16 efforts to provide this information to patients, families and health care providers; (iii) the effects
17 of the informational resources on patient outcomes; and (iv) obstacles encountered in
18 disseminating informational resources. The department shall incorporate public input in the
19 development of the report.
20 SECTION 3. The department of public health shall conduct a statewide campaign to raise
21 public awareness about SUDEP and other epilepsy-related mortalities.
